  <!-- About -->
  <section id="about" class="section">
    <div class="container section-inner">
      <div class="section-header">
        <h2>About Me</h2>
        <p class="section-kicker">Who I am and what I care about</p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid two-col">
        <div>
          <p>
            I am a Finance & Insurance Manager and business student who works at the intersection of
            finance, urban policy, and design. During the day I work in auto finance. Outside of work
            I build models, research economic inequality, and study how cities either expand or choke off opportunity.
          </p>
          <p>
            I founded the RCC Finance & Investment Banking Society to give community college students
            a real path into high finance. We learn valuation and modeling, host speakers from industry,
            and treat Riverside as a living lab for questions about capital, growth, and equity.
          </p>
          <p>
            This site connects three parts of my life: research on the wealth divide, documentary
            photography of Riverside and abroad, and leadership projects that try to move opportunity
            closer to the people who are usually shut out.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="about-highlight">
          <h3>Focus</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Economic inequality and urban policy</li>
            <li>Investment banking and capital flows</li>
            <li>City form, infrastructure, and design</li>
            <li>Community leadership and access to opportunity</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Research -->
  <section id="research" class="section alt">
    <div class="container section-inner">
      <div class="section-header">
        <h2>Research</h2>
        <p class="section-kicker">The Price of the Dream and related work</p>
      </div>

      <article class="research-card">
        <h3>The Price of the Dream: Confronting America’s Wealth Divide</h3>
        <p class="research-meta">
          Original research project, Riverside City College Student Research Conference
        </p>

        <p class="research-abstract-label">Abstract</p>
        <p class="research-abstract">
          This project examines how the American wealth divide is produced and sustained through
          the everyday structures of policy and place. Using Riverside and the Inland Empire as a
          case study, I connect tax policy, housing markets, and labor conditions to the spatial
          realities that people actually live in, such as long commutes, fragmented transit, and
          concentrated poverty. Drawing on economic data, urban planning research, and on-the-ground
          observation, I argue that inequality is not an accident or a temporary glitch in the market,
          but the result of deliberate choices about what and whom our cities are designed to serve.
        </p>
        <p class="research-abstract">
          The paper proposes reforms that treat equity as a design problem as much as a moral one:
          more progressive tax structures, aggressive investment in affordable and mixed income housing,
          and land use decisions that shorten distances between home, work, and essential services.
          By pairing quantitative analysis with the physical and emotional experience of moving through
          a city like Riverside, the project argues that closing the wealth divide requires changing both
          how capital flows and how space is built.
        </p>

        <div class="research-actions">
          <a href="assets/research/price-of-the-dream.pdf" class="btn primary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            Read full paper (PDF)
          </a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <div class="grid two-col research-notes">
        <div>
          <h4>In progress</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Essays on transit, commute time, and social mobility</li>
            <li>Short pieces on zoning, redlining, and modern exclusion</li>
            <li>Case studies that link financial models to neighborhood outcomes</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4>Planned directions</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>Comparative studies of Inland Empire and coastal metro areas</li>
            <li>Blending urban photography with data storytelling</li>
            <li>Deeper work on how capital markets shape the built environment</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Photography -->
  <section id="photography" class="section">
    <div class="container section-inner">
      <div class="section-header">
        <h2>Photography</h2>
        <p class="section-kicker">Cities as living archives</p>
      </div>

      <p class="section-intro">
        I use photography to document the textures of the city: facades at golden hour, empty streets
        after closing time, and the faces of people who keep the place running. This work sits next to
        my research because policy is abstract until you see who lives inside it.
      </p>

