  <!-- Community / Leadership -->
  <section id="leadership" class="section alt">
    <div class="container section-inner">
      <div class="section-header">
        <h2>Community and Leadership</h2>
        <p class="section-kicker">RCC Finance & Investment Banking Society and beyond</p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid two-col">
        <div>
          <h3>RCC Finance & Investment Banking Society</h3>
          <p>
            I founded the RCC Finance & Investment Banking Society to prove that community college students
            can compete for the same roles as students from target schools. We build skills in valuation,
            Excel, and deal analysis, and we connect those skills back to the communities we come from.
          </p>
          <ul class="bulleted">
            <li>Founder and President, Riverside City College</li>
            <li>Structured training on accounting, valuation, and modeling</li>
            <li>Guest speakers from investment banks and advisory firms</li>
            <li>Planned firm visits and pitch competitions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>Programs and events</h3>
          <ul class="bulleted">
            <li>Finance career workshops for RCC students</li>
            <li>Financial literacy sessions and informal mentoring</li>
            <li>Club events that connect technical skills with local issues</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="small-note">
            Here I will add photos from pitch nights, guest speaker sessions, and trip snapshots
            as we build the club archive.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Vision -->
  <section id="vision" class="section">
    <div class="container section-inner">
      <div class="section-header">
        <h2>Future Vision</h2>
        <p class="section-kicker">Where I want this work to go</p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid two-col">
        <div>
          <p>
            I want to use finance and urban planning to design fairer cities. That means treating a capital
            stack and a zoning map as two sides of the same question. Who gets to live near jobs. Who spends
            hours in traffic. Who benefits when a neighborhood is labeled up and coming, and who is quietly
            priced out.
          </p>
          <p>
            In practice, this looks like pushing into investment banking and urban research at the same time.
            I want to understand how deals get done, how money moves, and how those decisions land on specific
            blocks and buildings. Long term, I see myself working on projects where community outcomes are
            measured with the same seriousness as returns.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p>
            This site is a living record of that path. As my research deepens, as the RCC Finance & Investment
            Banking Society grows, and as I keep shooting new cities, I will keep updating this space.
          </p>
          <p>
            If you are reading this as an admissions officer, a recruiter, or a future collaborator, this is
            the core of what I am building toward: cities where opportunity is not an accident, but something
            we design on purpose.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

